\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  So, I hope you now have an idea about the most accepted theory of how the 
sun and the solar system were formed. In fact, many new observations are showing major problems with this traditional view of planetary formation. For example, some scientists are now saying that the time frame is all wrong - that planets may have formed 
m
uch more quickly than the standard theory suggests. And there are other problems too when it comes to the formation of the outer planets, especially about how and where they formed. Some people are saying we may have to revise or even abandon the standard
 model. As with many theories in science, it's pretty much open to revision.}{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913 
\par But now let's move on to an examination of what happened inside the Earth in its early stages. I know some of you have studied Earth formation in other courses, but I want to fill in the gaps for those who haven't got this background. OK. So, about 4.6 }{
\insrsid6691261 billion}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  years ago, the Earth was pretty much organized into a sphere and had a temperature of around 1,000 degrees. Note also that all the material forming the planet was randomly sp
read around. But at that point three things were happening which caused the planet to heat up further. So, what kind of things would cause the planet to get hotter?
\par }{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Man Student:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  All the impacts from rocks and meteorites and other stuff in space. When that
 stuff hits the Earth, that impact energy would be converted into heat energy. That would heat it up.
\par }{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  OK. Good. Well, sure, that's one of the three main causes of this heating. Certainly at the upper levels - the crust of the planet. Now what else?
\par }{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Woman Student:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  Uh, the sun would have heated it.
\par }{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913 
 Well, yes. But I don't just mean warming the surface. We're talking about heating the planet right down to the core, the center. How did the Earth heat up so that iron, for example, could melt? That's at about 2,000 degrees Celsius.
\par }{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Man Student:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  What about radiation?
\par }{\insrsid7090824 
\par }{\b\insrsid7090824\charrsid7090824 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid7090824\charrsid536913  Yes, that's it. That is probably the most important cause of the heating up. Radioactive elements, such as uranium, within the rocks inside the pl
anet decayed, and as they did so heat was generated. In fact, radioactive decay is still going on but at a slower rate than previously - since, of course, well, there isn't nearly as much radioactive material left - due to this decay over time.}{
\insrsid7090824 
